WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:10.500
Welcome! If you've just signed up for Terrascope, or you're curious about what it can do for your research,

2
00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:17.000
you're in the right place. This video is designed for absolute beginners.

3
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Terrascope is a free Belgian online platform that gives you access to tons of data

4
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.500
and tools to analyze it without needing a high-end computer.

5
00:00:32.500 --> 00:00:39.300
This video is an initial tour of the three main parts of Terrascope:

6
00:00:39.300 --> 00:00:40.500
the Viewer, the EOplaza, and the cloud processing environment.

7
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
This is the Terrascope homepage, your central hub.

8
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
From here you can access documentation, news, and advanced training.

9
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.500
In this video we'll focus on the Viewer and the EOplaza,

10
00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:57.500
and then we'll see how they connect to cloud processing.

11
00:00:57.500 --> 00:01:01.500
Don't worry, we'll clarify everything.

12
00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:07.150
The Viewer lets you see satellite images without downloading anything.

13
00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:13.650
You can zoom in and out and browse through recent images from different satellites.

14
00:01:13.650 --> 00:01:20.650
For example, selecting the Sentinel-2 NDVI layer gives you a visual of vegetation greenness.

15
00:01:20.650 --> 00:01:26.150
You can also export the current view as a PNG image,

16
00:01:26.150 --> 00:01:31.650
or download the actual data layers like NDVI, SCL, or the quicklook for further use.

17
00:01:32.150 --> 00:01:39.650
Now, if you want to generate information products or analyses, you go to the EOplaza.

18
00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:46.150
This is a catalogue of services where you can find derived information products,

19
00:01:46.150 --> 00:01:52.150
like crop-type classification maps, flood extent maps, or air quality data.

20
00:01:52.150 --> 00:01:58.150
Let's take NDWI, the Normalized Difference Water Index, as an example.

21
00:01:58.150 --> 00:02:04.650
NDWI is related to plant water content, and therefore a good proxy for plant water stress.

22
00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:10.650
After selecting it, you click 'Get started' and it will open the openEO Web Editor , 

23
00:02:10.650 --> 00:02:17.150
that's the cloud processing environment I mentioned.

24
00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:21.990
Here you can run NDWI without writing code.

25
00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:25.990
You define your area of interest and the time period,

26
00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:30.990
choose the output format, for example, GTIFF in this case , 

27
00:02:30.990 --> 00:02:36.990
and run the workflow directly in your browser with synchronous processing.

28
00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:43.490
For larger areas, you can submit it as a batch job that runs on Terrascope's servers.

29
00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:47.990
The results appear right here. You can explore them on an interactive map,

30
00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:54.490
download them, or even export the workflow as Python or R code

31
00:02:54.490 --> 00:02:59.990
if you want to reuse it later.

32
00:02:59.990 --> 00:03:05.490
Let's quickly recap what you've learned in this video.

33
00:03:05.490 --> 00:03:13.990
Viewer: look at satellite images, zoom, change layers, export PNG or download data.

34
00:03:13.990 --> 00:03:23.990
EOplaza: a catalogue of products like crop maps or indices such as NDWI.

35
00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:31.490
openEO Web Editor: run analyses without code.

36
00:03:31.490 --> 00:03:39.990
You pick your area, time, and output format,

37
00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:44.990
then run synchronously in your browser, or as a batch job for larger areas.

38
00:03:45.040 --> 00:03:53.040
You've just seen the big picture: how to view, find, and process Earth observation data on Terrascope , 

39
00:03:53.040 --> 00:03:58.040
all for free, all in the cloud.

40
00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:05.040
Now that you understand the three main tools, it's time to get hands on with the first one.

41
00:04:05.040 --> 00:04:14.740
In the next video, 'Your first look: the Viewer', we'll walk step by step through navigating the Viewer.

